## INVESTIGATION  OF  GASIFICATION  REACTIONS AND  H2/CO  RATIO  ANALYSIS  FOR  RICE  HUSK AIR  GASIFICATION  SIMULATION

by

## Dillibabu VENUGOPAL  a , Lakshmanan THANGAVELU  b , and Anbazhaghan NATARAJAN  c*

a Department of Automobile Engineering, KCG College of Technology, Anna University, Chennai, India b Department of Mechanical Engineering, SRM Institute of Science and Technology, Kattankulathur, India c Department of Mechanical Engineering, VRS College of Engineering and Technology, Anna University, Villuppuram, India

Original scientific paper https://doi.org/10.2298/TSCI220119087V

The syngas generated during gasification process is used for industrial process heat,  power  generation  and  chemical  feedstock  production.  Gas  composition, H2/CO and CO/CO2 ratios are the deciding factors for producer gas end-use. In the present work, rice husk air gasification simulation is carried out by non -stoichiometric equilibrium model using Gibbs free energy minimization by FactSage 6.3 software. Influence of gasification reactions and effect of temperature, equivalence ratio on gas composition was studied. The analysis was carried out to study the effect of operating conditions on producer gas heating value and gasification efficiency at various H /CO ratios. Increase in temperature improves 2 H2 and CO formation in water gas reaction and reduction of H  formation was 2 observed in water gas shift reaction due to endothermic behavior change. For all  the  values  of  the  equivalence  ratio,  ϕ,  an  increase  in  temperature  reduces the H2 /CO and enhances the CO/CO  ratio due to higher CO formation. For a 2 particular, ϕ, value, maximum gas heating value and gasification efficiency were obtained at low H /CO ratio. 2

Key words: rice husk, air gasification, gasification simulation, H /CO ratio, 2 gas heating value, gasification efficiency

## Introduction

Biomass gasification is the thermo-chemical conversion process used to generate pro -ducer gas/syngas from solid biomass fuels. Rice husk is largely produced in India, every year 24 millionns of rice husk is produced [1]. The main constituents of producer gas are CO, CO 2 and H . Gas calorific value and gasification efficiency depends on the composition of producer 2 gas. The gas composition of producer gas depends on fuel property, gasifying medium and op -erating conditions [2, 3]. High formation of combustible gases leads to improved calorific value and gasification efficiency. Syngas was commonly used in the petrochemical and metallurgical process and H /CO ratio of the syngas decides its final use. Syngas with a high H /CO ratio is 2 2 used for hydrogen production, syngas with H /CO ratio value of two is used for raw materi 2 -

* Corresponding author, e-mail: anbazhaghan1968@gmail.com

al production such as synthetic fuels, oxo-alcohols, ethylene glycol, acetic acid and dimethyl ether. The H /CO ratio is not a constraint for syngas use in boilers and turbines and CO/CO 2 2 ratio is the index scale for process completion [4, 5].

Ardebili et  al. [4]  investigated  the  influence  of  operating  parameters  on  low  tem -perature gasification using a mathematical model for raw material production. Fischer-Troph (FT) process is used to convert H  and CO mixture into liquid HC, the requirement of syn 2 -gas for the FT process depends on high formation of H  and CO. The H /CO ratio and CO/ 2 2 CO ratio  were  used  to  evaluate  the  effectiveness  of  the  process.  Carbonaceous  materials 2 are  gasified  with  steam  and  oxygen  to  improve  the  H /CO  ratio  at  low  temperature  condi 2 -tions  for  the  conformity  of  the  FT  process.  Tristantini et  al. [5]  carried  out  the  feasibil -ity  study  of  syngas  with  different  H /CO  ratios  for  FT  synthesis  using  Co/γ-Al O 2 2 3 and Co-Re/γ-Al O3. A gas mixture with a low H /CO ratio decreased the CO conversion and slightly 2 2 increased the HC formation. The conversion of CH  into syngas is known as steam reforming 4 reaction, syngas with high H /CO ratio is produced during steam reforming and less CO  for 2 2 -mation takes place compared to the gasification process. The complete conversion of CH 4 is not possible in reforming reaction due to equilibrium constraints. Cao et al. [6] injected CH 4 into the pyrolysis and gasification zone of the co-gasification reactor to modify the H /CO ratio 2 of the syngas for the coal gasification process. Coal gasification reactivity correlated to the gas yield and H /CO ratio of syngas depends on the H/C ratio of the coal. 2

Buragohain et al. [7] have reported optimization of biomass (sawdust, rice husk, bam -boo dust) air gasification and air-steam gasification in terms of feedstock for FT synthesis and decentralized power generation. Non-stoichiometric equilibrium model (SOLGASMIX) was used for optimization by FactSage software. The H  and CO content in producer gas and H / 2 2 CO ratio were assessed for FT synthesis. The heating value of gas mixture and overall effi -ciency were analyzed with relevance to decentralized power generation. The gas heating value remained constant after 700 °C and operating the gasifier above 700 °C leading to energy loss. Low and high equivalence ratio resulted in significant unconverted carbon and CO  formation, 2 respectively. Syngas is commonly produced from steam reforming of natural gas, partial oxida -tion of heavy oils and gasification of coal and biomass [8]. Syngas production is an important step in the production of derived products, it influences the cost and impact on the environment. The H  and CO formation plays an important role in the gasification process. Syngas with H / 2 2 CO ratio of two is required for methanol production and FT synthesis; synthesis of ethanol, dimethyl ether and oxo-alcohols requires H /CO ratio of 1 [7]. 2

In the present work, the producer gas composition of rice husk air gasification was determined at different operating conditions using the non-stoichiometric equilibrium model. Influence of gasification reactions and effect of temperature, equivalence ratio on gas compo -sition was studied. The H /CO ratio, CO/CO 2 2 ratio were evaluated, an analysis was carried out to find a suitable operating condition for maximum H /CO ratio attainment. Gas heating value 2 and gasification efficiency values were calculated at different H /CO ratios for the simulation of 2 rice husk air gasification process.

## Methodology

Simulation of rice husk air gasification was carried out by non-stoichiometric equi -librium  model  using  FactSage  software,  Gibbs  free  energy  minimization  was  employed  to find out the gas composition. Many researchers, Li et al. [9], Altafini et al. [10], and Yoshida et al. [11] used equilibrium model to predict the performance of commercial gasifiers and closer agreement with experimental result was experienced.

Equilibrium composition of producer gas was determined by finding the number of atoms (C, H, and O) for reactants and the number of C, H  and O atoms in each product. Gibbs 2 free energy of formation for each product was evaluated at individual temperature. The min -imum thermodynamic potential equation was developed for each product using the Lagrange multiplier method, given by eq. (1). Many researchers, Zainal et al. [3], Lan et al. [12], and Shabbarand Janajreh [13] used Lagrange multiplier method to determine final gas composition of  non-stoichiometric  equilibrium  model. The  material  balance  equation  was  developed  for each element, represented by eq. (2). Products minimum thermodynamic potential equations and material balance equations are solved simultaneously along with a mole fraction equation for finding the mole composition of each product:

Product composition of water gas reaction, water gas shift reaction and Boudouard reaction were determined for the temperature range 200-1200 °C using FactSage software. ## Gasification simulation procedure

Non-stoichiometric equilibrium model based on Gibbs free energy minimization us -ing the Lagrange multiplier iterative method was adopted in FactSage software. The objective function of the model was subjected to mass balance and non-negativity of the number of moles to find the equilibrium composition of final products. Equilib module was selected from the calculate section of the FactSage software main window. Rice husk elemental composition, air quantity, temperature and pressure of the gasification process were the input detail. The elemen -tal composition of rice husk is taken from Karmakar et al. [8], shown in tab. 1.

Air  quantity  required  for  gasification  of  rice  husk  was  established  by  stoichiometric calculations. Rice husk elemental composition entered along with the air quantity in the reactant window of the software. The atmospheric condition was taken as the initial condition and the most stable phase was selected for the reactants. Simulation conditions were specified at the menu window, the temperature range was 600-800°C and the equivalence ratios were 0.25, 0.35, and 0.45. The menu window of FactSage software is shown in fig. 1. From the gas composition result, H /CO ratio, CO/CO ratio, gas heating value and gasification efficiency were determined. 2 2

## Model validation

In rice husk air gasification simulation, the simulation parameters were T = 600-800°C and ϕ = 0.25-0.45. Simulation results were compared with the experimental value of Karmakar et al . [8]. The simulation result has an average RMS error of 3.59. The difference in gas com -position of simulation result with literature value is shown in fig. 2. For extensive details, refer to the author's previous publications [17, 18].

## Result and discussion

Gasification is a complex  process,si -multaneous  chemical  reactions  occur  during gasification. The  final  composition  of  the  gas mixture depends on the individual chemical re -actions that occur during gasification [19, 20]. Water-gas reaction, water gas shift reaction and Boudouard reactions are predominant reactions for  combustible  gas  production  [21-23]. With the exception of the water gas shift reaction, the other two reactions are endothermic.

## Influence of gasification reactions on gas composition

An  increase  in  temperature  favours  the formation of H  and CO contents due to the im 2 -provement of the endothermic reactions [24, 25]. Char  formed  during  gasification  reacts  with steam released during the drying stage to pro -duce H  and CO. Formed CO further reacts to 2 form CO  and H . The produced CO 2 2 2 reduced into CO while reacting with the bed char. The H  formation depends on water gas and water 2 gas shift reaction. The CO improvement occurs due to water gas and Boudouard reaction [2426]. The reactions proceed until the char con -version  occurs. Water  gas  reaction,  water  gas

## Effect of temperature on gas composition

The temperature of the rice husk air gas -ification varied from 650-725 °C for the equiv -alence  ratio  of  0.25.  The  H   and  CO  contents 2 were  improved  with  temperature  raise,  CO 2 and  CH   contents  were  reduced.  The  H   and 4 2 CO reached a maximum value of 17.97% and 35.53%,  respectively,  at  725  °C.  An  increase in temperature reduced the methane content by thermal  cracking  and  reforming  reactions  [22, 23]. An increase in temperature reduced the CO 2 content due to the Boudouard reaction and the reverse  water  gas  shift  reaction  [25,  26].  For ϕ = 0.35 and ϕ = 0.45,a slight decrease of the H 2 content was observed after 725 °C and 650 °C, respectively. The H  reached a maximum value 2 of  14.55%,  11.69%,  and  CO  reached  29.66%, 22.85%  at ϕ =  0.35, ϕ =0.45,  respectively, shown in fig. 5.

## Effect of equivalence ratio on gas composition

The lower limit of the equivalence ratio was decided by the quantity of gasifying medi -um required to burn the rice husk and to pro -duce  sufficient  heat  for  endothermic  reactions [8,  25].  The  effect  of  the  equivalence  ratio  on gas  composition  was  analyzed  for  650 ° C,

700 ° C, and 725 ° C is shown in fig. 6. A high equivalence  ratio  during  gasification  leads  to the combustion of rice husk. An increase in the equivalence ratio caused a decrease in the com -bustible gases due to the oxidation reaction [2731]. Augmenting ϕ value from 0.25-0.45 at 650 ° C decreased the H  and CO content by 5.28% 2 and 2.14%, respectively. At 700  C, H , and CO ° 2 content were decreased by 6.13% and 10.29%, respectively, at 725  C, the reduction was 6.51% ° and 13.58%, respectively. The prevalent reduc -tion of H  and CO content was noticed at 725 2 ° C.

## The H2/CO ratio and CO/CO2 ratio analysis

At ϕ = 0.25, increase in temperature de -creases the H /CO ratio due to the higher for 2 -mation  of  CO  than  H .  The  decreasing  trend 2 is applicable to other equivalence ratio condi -tions. The maximum H /CO ratio of 0.93 was 2 attained at 600 °C for ϕ =0.35. At ϕ = 0.25, the temperature change from 650-725 °C leads to 32.32% of H /CO ratio reduction, 22.05% and 2 8.13% reduction was observed for ϕ = 0.35 and 0.45, respectively. At 650 °C, the increase in ϕ value decreases H /CO ratio due to the higher 2 reduction of H  than CO. At 700 °C and 725 °C, 2 H /CO ratio decreased for 2 ϕ value change from 0.25-0.35, further increase in ϕ value improves H /CO  ratio  due  to  the  higher  CO  reduction. 2 The H /CO ratio and CO/CO  ratio of rice husk 2 2 air gasification is shown in fig. 7.

Increase  in  temperature  enhances  CO/ CO  ratio for all the equivalence ratios due to 2 the  increment  of  CO  content  and  the  corre -sponding  reduction  of  CO   content  [4,  5,  302 32]. At ϕ =  0.25,  maximum  CO/CO   ratio  of 2 4.74 was attained for 725 °C. The temperature change from 650-725 °C leads to 2.31 times of CO/CO  ratio improvement. At 650 °C increase 2 in ϕ value  initially  augments  the  CO/CO 2 ratio and then decreases due to CO and CO 2 reduction with equivalence ratio. At 700 °C and 725 °C, the CO/CO  ratio decreases with the 2 equivalence ratio due to the reduction of CO and  the  corresponding  increase  of  the  CO 2 content.

## Conclusion

Rice husk  air  gasification  simulation  was  carried  out  by  a  non-stoichiometric  equilibri -um model based on Gibbs free energy minimization using FactSage 6.3 software. The Influence of  gasification  reactions  and  effect  of  operating  conditions  on  final  gas  composition  was  studied. Increase in temperature favours the formation of H  and CO contents due to the improvement 2 of endothermic reactions. The H  formation depends on water gas and water gas shift reaction, 2 CO improvement occurs due to water gas and Boudouard reaction. A reduction in H 2 formation after 700 °C was observed in water gas shift reaction due to the endothermic behaviour change. The H  and CO reached a maximum value of 17.97 % and 35.53 %, respectively, at 725 °C for 2

ϕ = 0.25. Increase in the equivalence ratio reduces the combustible gas content of the produc -er gas. Increase in temperature decreased the H /CO ratio and improved CO/CO  ratio for all 2 2 equivalence ratios. The maximum H /CO ratio of 0.93 was attained at 600 2 ° C and ϕ = 0.35 and CO/CO  ratio of 4.74 was attained at 725 2 ° C and ϕ = 0.25. For operating conditions with same H /CO ratio value, better gas heating value and gasification efficiency were attained at 2 higher CO/CO  ratios. Maximum gasification efficiency of 58.57% was attained at 725 °C for 2 ϕ = 0.25 with LHV = 6.54 MJ/Nm 3 . For all the equivalence ratios, increase in temperature enhances the gas lower heating value and gasification efficiency with corresponding H /CO 2 reduction.
